stylometry:
My group has made a couple of plans for the project.  We have narrowed it down to a couple of ideas.  I used to intern for the Lake County Captains Baseball ticket sales team.  They struggled to get the stadium filled.  I think it would be beneficial for them to know how many tickets they need to sell to break-even, or make a profit on a single night.  They have so many promotional items, I would be curious how many people need to be brought in to make a profit.  We could create a decision making model on Excel.  The constraints would be fairly easy, one would be the maximum amount of people that are allowed in the stadium.  

Another idea is where Andy worked.  Andy used to work for a construction company.  He brought up the idea of how many projects would need to be done to pay for the equipment and parts used.  This would be a good problem because I'm sure this question is asked frequently by construction companies.  

Right now, I am interning for the Downtown Painesville Organization.  They focus their marketing through email and social networking, I would be curious as to how many emails need to be sent out, to get a certain percentage of returns.  They use the email program Constant Contact, which tracks the amount of links opened in an email, this would be good data to use to get a better accurate number.

As a group, we have a couple solid ideas.  We need to talk further and finalize which idea would be best suited for us.
